"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422311","Home Office","false","2015-11-04","<p>The Immigration Rules provide designated routes through which individuals can choose to apply for leave to remain in the UK depending on their circumstances. The requirements of each route are set out in published guidance. It is for individuals to raise any grounds that they wish to be considered and provide any supporting evidence regarding their personal circumstances.</p><p>Applications for leave to remain in the UK are considered on a case-by-case basis, including any claims about personal issues, in accordance with the relevant Immigration Rules and the Secretary of State’s published guidance on the application of these.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-11-04T17:20:31.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422311/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422311/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-19","Immigration: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken to ensure that assessments of applications for leave to remain in the UK provide sufficient personal consideration to meet the individual needs of applicants.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","12275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422312","Home Office","false","2015-10-23","<p>The Home Office provides funding for the necessary numberof Prevent co-ordinators in priority areas. The list of areas is kept under review.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-10-23T12:31:43.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422312/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422312/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422312/answer/previousversion/25172","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-19","Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2015 to Question 11726, how many Prevent co-ordinators are employed in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422313","Home Office","false","2015-10-26","<p>I have received no representations about the use of CCTV cameras with facial recognition and biometric tracking capabilities.</p><p>The use of any CCTV system operating in a public place in England and Wales (whether or not any facial recognition or biometric tracking technology is being used) is subject to the Surveillance Camera Code of Practice, issued as guidance under the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012. The police, as a relevant authority, are duty bound to have regard to the Code when performing their functions. Any use of such technology for covert investigative purposes by a public authority would be subject to the requirements of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 and its related Code of Practice. Further, the use and disclosure of personal data, such as CCTV images, is generally governed by the Data Protection Act 1998.</p><p>Information on the fields of data which any CCTV system operator may use to identify individuals of interest is not held centrally. Further, any person (including those not suspected of an offence) may make a subject access request to a police force in respect of personal information which is held about them (including CCTV images). In broad terms, pursuant to the Code of Practice on the Management of Police Information (MOPI) and accompanying guidance published by the College of Policing, this should trigger a review of whether or not to delete such material based on an assessment of danger to the public and its value for policing purposes.</p><p>It is the longstanding policy of successive Governments not to comment on intelligence matters.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","12290 ; 12291 ; 12292 ; 12293 ; 12295 ; 12296","2015-10-26T16:52:16.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422313/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422313/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-19","CCTV","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations she has received from civil liberties campaign groups on the operation of and use of data from CCTV cameras with facial recognition and biometric tracking capabilities.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12294"
