"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422334","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-22","<p>Information on the enforcement of financial impositions is contained within an annex to <em>Criminal Court Statistics Bulletin</em> published quarterly by the Ministry of Justice.</p><br /><p>The data for the period April to September 2015 will be published on 17 December 2015. This will separately identify the monetary values of the criminal courts charge imposed and collected since 13 April 2015.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-10-22T16:48:54.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422334/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422334/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-19","Criminal Proceedings: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the monetary value has been of criminal courts charges (a) imposed and (b) collected since the introduction of those charges.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","12363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422335","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-19","<p>The information requested can be found in the table below.</p><br /><p><strong>Crown Court sittings at Warrington (days):</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Courtroom 1</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Courtroom 2</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>County Court courtroom</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January to December 2013</p></td><td><p>132</p></td><td><p>120</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January to December 2014</p></td><td><p>105</p></td><td><p>182</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January to September 2015</p></td><td><p>87</p></td><td><p>104</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>There are two dedicated Crown courtrooms in Warrington Combined Court, which also houses the County Court. The final column therefore sets out the number of days sat in County Court accommodation when, exceptionally, the Crown courtrooms were unavailable.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-11-19T14:11:31.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422335/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422335/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-19","Crown Courts: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on how many days the Crown Court sat in each court chamber at Warrington in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015.","false","Biography information for David Mowat","Warrington South","David Mowat","12336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422336","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-23","<p>Information on all deaths in prison custody and self-harm incidents, including at HMP Foston Hall, can be found in the Safety in Custody statistics which are published quarterly at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/safety-in-custody-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/safety-in-custody-statistics</a>.</p><br /><p>NOMS does not record ‘attempted suicide’ as a category of incident as the intention of the prisoner may not be known reliably.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-10-23T10:32:41.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422336/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422336/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-19","Foston Hall Prison: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people (a) attempted to take and (b) took their own lives at Foston Hall Prison, Derbyshire, was in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","12322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422337","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-26","<p>The target staffing figure for Prison Officers at Foston Hall is 90.50. The actual Staff in Post as at 30 September 2015 is 85.03. There are currently six prison officers going through the vetting process and one with a start date to add to this figure so this will provide a total of 92.03 against a target of 90.50. The excess number of staff will cover any staff who are leaving due to internal promotions that are currently in process.</p><br /><p>In order to monitor compliance with the staffing rate, the data is captured locally and fed in to a national planning tool that provides information to a regional workforce planning meeting where the situation is assessed monthly. This then feeds into the central National Offender Management Service planning figures.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-10-26T13:48:37.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422337/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422337/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-19","Foston Hall Prison: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the expected staffing rate at Foston Hall Prison, Derbyshire, is; and how often his Department assesses compliance with that rate.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","12323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422338","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-27","<p>At Foston Hall, prisoners are expected to spend 6.25 hours a day out of their cells in order to take part in work, training or education opportunities thatsupport their rehabilitation. This daily activity structure was implemented on 31 August 2015 andis monitored at local, regional and national levels.</p><br /><p>In addition to the activity structure, as with all prisons in England and Wales, there is a statutory requirement to give prisoners 30 minutes in the open air on a daily basis. There is also an agreement with National Offender Management Commissioners which applies to all prisons in their Service Level Agreements, that prisoners should receive 2.5 hours per week PE. These national requirements are also in place at Foston Hall</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-10-27T16:52:26.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422338/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422338/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-19","Foston Hall Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what guidance or direction his Department has given on the amount of time that inmates at Foston Hall Prison, Derbyshire, should spend outside their cells; and what monitoring of such time his Department carries out.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","12324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422339","Leader of the House","false","2015-10-22","<p>None.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2015-10-22T06:19:17.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422339/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422339/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-10-19","Leader of the House of Commons: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of the Leader of the House being elected by the whole House.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","12452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422340","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-10-26","<p>Negotiations on the proposed General Data Protection Regulation are still continuing and our negotiating position has taken into account the likely impact on Government Departments, NDPBs and agencies. Once the outcome of trilogue negotiations between the Council of the European Union, the European Parliament and the Commission are complete, and the Regulation has been adopted, the liabilities will be further assessed. There will then follow a maximum implementation period of two years. Between now and then, Government departments who will be affected by the Regulation are closely involved in work led by the Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport to consider the implications of the text as it develops through the negotiating process.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2015-10-26T11:42:26.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422340/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422340/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-10-19","Northern Ireland Office: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps her Department has taken to prepare for the implementation of the proposed General Data Protection Regulation; which non-departmental public bodies (NDPBs) overseen by her Department will be affected by that Regulation; and what estimate she has made of the potential liability of her Department and its NDPBs in connection with that proposed Regulation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","12428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422341","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-10-26","<p>This Government has put considerable effort into ensuring the Police Service of Northern Ireland is properly resourced to tackle the terrorist threat. We have provided £231million between 2011 and 2016, and this support has been crucial in helping to ensure that the PSNI’s investigative and operational capacity is effective.</p><p>As the Government’s Northern Ireland Manifesto at the election stated, we will always give the fullest possible backing to the PSNI.</p><br /> <br />","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-10-26T11:49:27.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422341/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422341/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-10-19","Electronic Surveillance: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if she will make extra funding available for digital technology so that full monitoring of dissident Republicans can be maintained.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","12489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422342","Home Office","false","2015-11-16","<p>The Government’s position on the Wilson Doctrine was set out by the Prime Minister in a written ministerial statement made on 4 November 2015.</p><p>As the Prime Minister made clear, the Wilson Doctrine has never been an absolute bar to the targeted interception of the communications of Members of Parliament or an exemption from the legal regime governing interception. The Doctrine recognised that there could be instances where interception might be necessary.</p><p>The Prime Minister announced that as matter of policy the PM will be consulted should there ever be a proposal to target any UK Parliamentarian’s communications under a warrant issued by a Secretary of State. This applies to Members of Parliament, members of the House of Lords, the Scottish Parliament, the Northern Ireland Assembly, the Welsh Assembly and UK members of the European Parliament. It applies to all activity authorised by a warrant issued by a Secretary of State: any instance of targeted interception and, electronic surveillance and equipment interference, when undertaken by the Security and Intelligence Agencies. This is in addition to the rigorous safeguards already in the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 (RIPA) and the Code of Practice issued under it which set out a series of robust safeguards for any instance of interception.</p><p>It is long standing policy of successive Governments neither to confirm nor deny any specific activity by the Security and Intelligence Agencies. Under the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 it is an offence for anyone to identify an individual interception warrant or an individual interception that takes place.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-11-16T17:35:11.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422342/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422342/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422342/answer/previousversion/25175","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-19","Members: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Wilson Doctrine has been consistently applied to the communications of the hon. Member for Lincoln since his election; and whether that hon. Member has been subject to surveillance.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","12436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422343","Home Office","false","2015-11-16","<p>The Government’s position on the Wilson Doctrine was set out by the Prime Minister in a written ministerial statement made on 4 November 2015.</p><p>As the Prime Minister made clear, the Wilson Doctrine has never been an absolute bar to the targeted interception of the communications of Members of Parliament or an exemption from the legal regime governing interception. The Doctrine recognised that there could be instances where interception might be necessary.</p><p>The Prime Minister announced that as matter of policy the PM will be consulted should there ever be a proposal to target any UK Parliamentarian’s communications under a warrant issued by a Secretary of State. This applies to Members of Parliament, members of the House of Lords, the Scottish Parliament, the Northern Ireland Assembly, the Welsh Assembly and UK members of the European Parliament. It applies to all activity authorised by a warrant issued by a Secretary of State: any instance of targeted interception and, electronic surveillance and equipment interference, when undertaken by the Security and Intelligence Agencies. This is in addition to the rigorous safeguards already in the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 (RIPA) and the Code of Practice issued under it which set out a series of robust safeguards for any instance of interception.</p><p>It is long standing policy of successive Governments neither to confirm nor deny any specific activity by the Security and Intelligence Agencies. Under the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 it is an offence for anyone to identify an individual interception warrant or an individual interception that takes place.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-11-16T17:23:41.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422343/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422343/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-19","Members: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Wilson Doctrine has been consistently applied to the communications of the hon. Member for Washington and Sunderland West; and whether that hon. Member has been subject to surveillance.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","12274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422344","Scotland Office","false","2015-10-26","<p>Negotiations on the proposed General Data Protection Regulation are still continuing and our negotiating position has taken into account the likely impact on Government Departments, NDPBs and agencies. Once the outcome of trilogue negotiations between the Council of the European Union, the European Parliament and the Commission are complete, and the Regulation has been adopted, the liabilities will be further assessed. There will then follow a maximum implementation period of two years. Between now and then, Government departments who will be affected by the Regulation are closely involved in work led by the Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport to consider the implications of the text as it develops through the negotiating process.</p><br />","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-10-26T11:05:05.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422344/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422344/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-10-19","Scotland Office: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the implementation of the proposed General Data Protection Regulation; and what estimate he has made of the potential liability of his Department in connection with that proposed Regulation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","12429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422345","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>Negotiations on the proposed General Data Protection Regulation are still continuing and our negotiating position has taken into account the likely impact on Government Departments, NDPBs and agencies. Once the outcome of tripartite negotiations between the Council of the European Union, the European Parliament and the Commission are complete, and the Regulation has been adopted, the liabilities will be further assessed. There will then follow a maximum implementation period of two years. Between now and then, Government departments who will be affected by the Regulation are closely involved in work led by the Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport to consider the implications of the text as it develops through the negotiating process.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-27T15:06:07.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422345/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422345/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Department for Transport: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the implementation of the proposed General Data Protection Regulation; which non-departmental public bodies (NDPBs) and agencies overseen by his Department will be affected by that Regulation; and what estimate he has made of the potential liability of his Department, its agencies and NDPBs in connection with that proposed Regulation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","12430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422346","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-22","<p>The Department expects that the industry electrification strategy will be published by Network Rail as a draft for consultation in early 2016, taking into account the outcome of the review by Sir Peter Hendy of Network Rail’s programme of rail investment.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-22T14:48:27.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422346/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422346/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 1 July 2015 to Question 4425, when he expects Network Rail to publish an update to its industry electrification strategy.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422347","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-22","<p>I am not aware of the Department for Transport having received any such complaints.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-22T14:15:36.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422347/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422347/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Bus Services: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many times his Department received complaints that an Oyster machine is not working properly on a London bus in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","12382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422348","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-23","<p>The Civil Aviation Authority keeps a record of all the permissions they have issued to fly commercial drones in UK airspace. However this does not extend to leisure users of drones. To address this issue The Department for Transport is currently looking at a range of options including regulation, registration and licensing options and a database to increase transparency on the use of drones for the general public. We intend to consult on all of these issues and other possible solutions in 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-23T13:09:19.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422348/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422348/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to monitor the use of drones in UK airspace.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","12485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422349","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-26","<p>The Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) of Phase One of HS2 includes predictions of maximum sound levels from HS2 trains on residential properties. This has informed the noise mitigation provided as part of the scheme. The maximum acceptable sound levels at night are set out in Information Paper E20.</p><br /><p>Phase Two will undertake an EIA that will include predictions of maximum sound levels from HS2 trains.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-26T11:11:01.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422349/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422349/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that peak noise measurements are used by HS2 Ltd when developing proposals on the night use of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","12280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422350","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-26","<p><strong></strong>The latest noise appraisal that has been completed for Phase Two of HS2 follows Government’s Transport Appraisal Guidance. This guidance evaluates the noise impact on residential properties near proposed HS2 infrastructure. The results of this appraisal are reported in the Sustainability Statement (July 2013) and include results with and without additional indicative noise mitigation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-26T11:06:27.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422350/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422350/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of noise on residents living across open land, with no sound barriers, from the proposed High Speed 2 route through Eddisbury.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","12282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422351","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>HS2 applies the aims of the Noise Policy Statement for England (2010) whichseeks to avoid, minimise and mitigate significant adverse impacts on health and quality of life. This is undertaken through the design, construction and operation of HS2 infrastructure. Phase One includes extensive noise mitigation to reduce impacts on communities, including rural ones.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-27T13:11:36.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422351/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422351/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that the effect of noise from High Speed 2 on rural communities is minimised.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","12283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422352","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-23","<p>Local authorities are best placed to assess the need for pavement parking controls in their area and the effectiveness of any restrictions in place. It would be for the relevant traffic authorities to conduct an assessment of legislation specific to London.</p><br /><p>Last year this Department received around a thousand communications from Guide Dogs campaigners in support of two Private Members’ Bills on pavement parking. Departmental officials met with Guide Dogs officials as recently as 13 October this year.</p><br /><p>Local authorities already have the powers to introduce enforceable pavement parking restrictions where they consider it appropriate. My Department’s guidance to local authorities makes clear that, during the appraisal of their parking policies, an authority should consider whether pavement parking is problematic in any part of its area. If it is, and is not covered by an existing Traffic Regulation Order, the authority should consider amending the existing Order or making a new one. We have issued councils with authorisation to place specifically designed traffic signs without the need for Whitehall approval.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","12298 ; 12299","2015-10-23T13:26:08.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422352/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422352/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Parking: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of legislation to prevent pavement parking in London.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422353","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-23","<p>Local authorities are best placed to assess the need for pavement parking controls in their area and the effectiveness of any restrictions in place. It would be for the relevant traffic authorities to conduct an assessment of legislation specific to London.</p><br /><p>Last year this Department received around a thousand communications from Guide Dogs campaigners in support of two Private Members’ Bills on pavement parking. Departmental officials met with Guide Dogs officials as recently as 13 October this year.</p><br /><p>Local authorities already have the powers to introduce enforceable pavement parking restrictions where they consider it appropriate. My Department’s guidance to local authorities makes clear that, during the appraisal of their parking policies, an authority should consider whether pavement parking is problematic in any part of its area. If it is, and is not covered by an existing Traffic Regulation Order, the authority should consider amending the existing Order or making a new one. We have issued councils with authorisation to place specifically designed traffic signs without the need for Whitehall approval.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","12297 ; 12299","2015-10-23T13:26:09.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422353/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422353/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent representations he has received from local authorities, charities and disability groups on pavement parking.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422354","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-23","<p>Local authorities are best placed to assess the need for pavement parking controls in their area and the effectiveness of any restrictions in place. It would be for the relevant traffic authorities to conduct an assessment of legislation specific to London.</p><br /><p>Last year this Department received around a thousand communications from Guide Dogs campaigners in support of two Private Members’ Bills on pavement parking. Departmental officials met with Guide Dogs officials as recently as 13 October this year.</p><br /><p>Local authorities already have the powers to introduce enforceable pavement parking restrictions where they consider it appropriate. My Department’s guidance to local authorities makes clear that, during the appraisal of their parking policies, an authority should consider whether pavement parking is problematic in any part of its area. If it is, and is not covered by an existing Traffic Regulation Order, the authority should consider amending the existing Order or making a new one. We have issued councils with authorisation to place specifically designed traffic signs without the need for Whitehall approval.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","12297 ; 12298","2015-10-23T13:26:09.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422354/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422354/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to tackle vehicle parking on pavements.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422355","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>Leeds City Council and the West Yorkshire Combined Authority as promoters of this scheme are responsible for providing the inquiry venue and facilities; paying for professional experts to present their case; and meeting the Planning Inspectorate’s costs in providing an Inspector. The Planning Inspectorate charged £157,162 for this inquiry, based on the time spent by the Inspector preparing for, travelling to and holding the inquiry; the time spent by the Inspector writing his report; and his travelling and subsistence. Other parties to the inquiry were responsible for meeting their own costs.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-27T13:22:40.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422355/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422355/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Trolleybuses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate he has made of the cost of the public inquiry into the New Generation Transport trolleybus scheme; and what he expects the final cost of that inquiry to be.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422356","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>We are considering the Inspector’s Report following the public inquiry, and will announce our decision shortly. My Right Honourable Friend the Secretary of State has delegated responsibility for this decision to my Noble Friend Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-27T14:05:24.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422356/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422356/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Trolleybuses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the public inquiry into the New Generation Transport trolleybus scheme to report.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","12301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422357","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-27","<p>The Government is currently considering the large amount of very detailed analysis contained in the Airports Commission’s final report before taking any decisions on next steps.</p><br /><p>The Airports Commission considered the costs associated with the Lakeside Energy from Waste Plant in its assessment of land acquisition costs. This is included in the report “<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/440369/cost-and-commercial-viability-cost-and-revenue-identification-update-heathrow-airport-north-west-runway.pdf" target="_blank"><em>Cost and Commercial Viability</em></a><em>: Cost and Revenue Identification Update Heathrow Airport North West Runway”. </em></p><br /><p>It is important to note that no decisions have been taken, but if the Government was minded to support the need for new runway capacity and concluded that the North-West runway at Heathrow was the preferred option for meeting this requirement, the planning and costs of moving the Energy from Waste Plant would be a matter for the airport to take forward with the owners of the site.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-10-27T13:17:12.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422357/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422357/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of moving the Lakeside Energy from Waste Plant from its current site; and what his policy is on whether that cost would be met by Heathrow Airport or the Government.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","12311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422358","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-22","<p>Local transport authorities across England are responsible for public transport in their local areas, as has been the case under previous Administrations. This includes the development of policies relating to local transport, including public transport, and the preparation and publication of a local transport plan. In the Metropolitan area of the West Midlands, this responsibility sits with the West Midlands Integrated Transport Authority.</p><br /><p>In the 2015 Summer Budget, the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced £5million for Midlands Connect, a partnership of Local Authorities and Local Enterprise Partnerships from across the Midlands, to develop its transport vision and strategy for transforming transport connectivity across the region in order to drive economic growth. Officials from the Department for Transport continue to work with Midlands Connect and the partnership launched their approach to this task today.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-22T13:59:39.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422358/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422358/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Public Transport: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department has taken to review the adequacy of public transport options in the West Midlands; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","12393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422359","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-22","<p>The Department for Transport has not undertaken a review of safety of the roads of highways in the West Midlands as this is a matter for the local highway authorities and Highways England.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-10-22T14:03:28.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422359/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422359/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Roads: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department has taken to review the safety of roads and highways in the West Midlands; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","12394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422360","Department for Transport","false","2015-10-22","<p>No Government decision has yet been taken on Crossrail 2 and the alignment is principally a matter for the Mayor of London.</p><br /><p>The recently established National Infrastructure Commission have been tasked with work to establish the best approach to large-scale investment in London’s transport infrastructure which may have implications for Crossrail 2 going forward. They will provide advice to Government by Budget 2016.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-10-22T14:21:41.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422360/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422360/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-10-19","Crossrail 2 Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to make an assessment of the case for an Eastern Branch of Crossrail 2 serving Hackney Central, Hackney Wick, Stratford, East Ham and Barking.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","12388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422361","Wales Office","false","2015-10-23","<p>Negotiations on the proposed General Data Protection Regulation are still continuing and our negotiating position has taken into account the likely impact on Government Departments, NDPBs and agencies. Once the outcome of trilogue negotiations between the Council of the European Union, the European Parliament and the Commission are complete, and the Regulation has been adopted, the liabilities will be further assessed. There will then follow a maximum implementation period of two years. Between now and then, Government departments who will be affected by the Regulation are closely involved in work led by the Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport to consider the implications of the text as it develops through the negotiating process.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2015-10-23T12:14:02.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422361/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422361/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-10-19","Wales Office: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the implementation of the proposed General Data Protection Regulation; and what estimate he has made of the potential liability of his Department in connection with that proposed Regulation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","12432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422362","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-26","<p>Jobcentre staff are trained to deal with a wide range of circumstances, offering a personalised approach.</p><p>In readiness for Universal Credit, Work Coaches will be multi skilled so they can work with the person to resolve a variety of issues or barriers preventing them securing employment. This is based on individual need rather than around particular groups or characteristics.</p><p>There has been no specific assessment made of the implications for the workload of Jobcentre Plus of providing appropriate advice and support to parents with children aged two, three and four who (a) have never been employed, (b) do not have five A*-C grades at GCSE, (c) have a history of addiction, (d) have mental health problems and (e) were formerly looked-after children.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-26T13:50:05.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422362/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422362/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Jobcentre Plus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the implications for the workload of Jobcentre Plus of providing appropriate advice and support to parents with children aged two, three and four who (a) have never been employed, (b) do not have five A* to C grades at GCSE, (c) have a history of addiction, (d) have mental health problems and (e) were formerly looked-after children.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","12345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422363","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>Negotiations on the proposed General Data Protection Regulation are still continuing and our negotiating position has taken into account the likely impact on Government Departments, NDPBs and agencies. Once the outcome of trilogue negotiations between the Council of the European Union, the European Parliament and the Commission are complete, and the Regulation has been adopted, the liabilities will be further assessed. There will then follow a maximum implementation period of two years. Between now and then, Government departments who will be affected by the Regulation are closely involved in work led by the Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport to consider the implications of the text as it develops through the negotiating process.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T17:27:12.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422363/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422363/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Department for Work and Pensions: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the implementation of the proposed General Data Protection Regulation; which non-departmental public bodies (NDPBs) and agencies overseen by his Department will be affected by that Regulation; and what estimate he has made of the potential liability of his Department, its agencies and NDPBs in connection with that proposed Regulation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","12433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422364","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-22","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to Question 11863 asked on 14 October 2015</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","12398","2015-10-22T09:59:48.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422364/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422364/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Universal Credit: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants in (a) Liverpool, Walton constituency and (b) Liverpool have appealed against sanctions; what the average length of sanctions in those areas was in the last 12 months; and how many such appeals were successful.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","12456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422365","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-26","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-26T14:06:49.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422365/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422365/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who are in receipt of employment and support allowance in (a) the work-related activity group and (b) the support group were initially assessed by a work capability assessment as being fit for work.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","12340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422366","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-22","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to Question 11863 asked on 14 October 2015</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","12456","2015-10-22T09:59:47.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422366/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422366/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Universal Credit: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants have been sanctioned in (a) Liverpool, Walton constituency and (b) Liverpool since the implementation of that policy.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","12398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422367","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-22","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. These are available on the Parliament website: <a href="http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html" target="_blank">http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-22T10:12:11.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422367/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422367/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Employment and Support Allowance: Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people with cancer who will be affected by proposals under the Welfare Reform and Work Bill to reduce the amount paid to new claimants in the employment and support allowance work related activity group.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","12386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422368","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-22","<p>We only collect limited data on those requests for a Short Term Benefit Advances that are refused although we do know that the vast majority of refusals are either because:<br>(i) There was a doubt about whether the claimant would be entitled to the benefit being claimed and, therefore, we could not be sure that there was any benefit to advance or <br>(ii) Actual benefit was paid instead, which is a better outcome for the claimant.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-22T13:29:23.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422368/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422368/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2015 to Question 11226, for what reasons decisions were not made on 118,039 of the applications his Department received in the period between October 2014 and September 2015 for Short Term Benefit Advance.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","12404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422369","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-22","<p>The Explanatory Memorandum that was published alongside the work allowance regulations contained the reference to the existing Universal Credit (UC) Impact Assessment. Whilst it is not standard practice to publish separate impact assessment for each change to the UC Regulations, Ministers gave full consideration to the impacts of these changes before the work allowance regulations were laid.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-22T09:45:20.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422369/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422369/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Universal Credit (Work Allowance) Amendment Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish an impact assessment of the Universal Credit (Work Allowance) Amendment Regulations 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","12392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422370","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-26","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-26T13:53:26.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422370/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422370/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employment and support allowance claimants who are in the support group were previously in the work-related activity group.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","12337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422371","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-22","<p>The information requested can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-10-22T09:56:09.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422371/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422371/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Universal Credit: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants there have been in (a) Liverpool, Walton constituency and (b) Liverpool city region since that policy's implementation.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","12397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422372","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>The Access to Work guidance and policy for fast track application requests is that applications are identified and marked as urgent then allocated to an advisory team on the same day. This includes the Access to Work adviser making contact with the customer on the same day to ensure that their request is progressed as far as possible to the point of decision on the level of support if possible.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T11:22:28.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422372/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422372/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what (a) guidelines and (b) recommended timescales exist for processing last-minute Access to Work extra support requests.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","12410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422373","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>Complaints about the assessment service offered by Capita are processed by Capita and not the Department for Work and Pensions.</p><br /><p>Capita has received a total of 1,288 complaints for 2015 in relation to their contractual delivery of the Personal Independence Payment Assessment process. This represents 1% of their total assessment referral volume.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T11:13:26.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422373/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422373/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Capita: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints his Department has received about the assessment assistance offered by CAPITA.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","12407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422374","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>There is no contractual agreement between DWP and assessment providers around the provision of audio equipment. If claimants wish for their assessments to be recorded they may do so using their own equipment, provided they comply with the conditions put in place which were outlined in the response provided to your previous question on this subject on 9 September 2015 and 16<sup>th</sup> of October 2015.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T11:09:27.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422374/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422374/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2015 to Question 11269, whether a personal independence payment assessment provider would be breaking the terms of its contract with his Department if it were to provide audio equipment for use in assessments which complied with the required specifications.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","12318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422375","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-27","<p>Information on Personal Independence Payment clearances by disallowance type (which includes ‘Disallowed post-referral to the AP’) is published on a quarterly basis and is available for both new claims and Disability Living Allowance reassessment claims from Stat-Xplore at <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Data is available at regional, parliamentary constituency and local authority level and can be broadly aggregated to give assessment provider level totals. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore is available at <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-27T11:17:35.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422375/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422375/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who had previously been in receipt of disability living allowance have been found ineligible for personal independence payments following assessment assistance by CAPITA.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","12408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422376","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-22","<p>Benefit cap statistics for the period to August 2015 have been pre-announced for publication on 5<sup>th</sup> November 2015, however the information you have requested cannot be provided due to disproportionate costs.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-22T16:27:23.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422376/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422376/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-19","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who were subject to the benefit cap between May 2015 and August 2015 had been in receipt of working tax credit at any point during the 12 months prior to May 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","12276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422835","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-22","<p>The Government announced last week that Professor Michael Waterson has been appointed to chair the independent review of consumer protection measures in the secondary ticket market. The review will look into existing protections for consumers and how tickets come to be available on the secondary market.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-10-22T16:23:30.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422835/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/422835/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-19","Tickets: Touting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to ensure that fans buying tickets for sporting and cultural events are not disadvantaged by organised gangs of online touts in the secondary ticket market.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","901735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423062","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-22","<p>Tackling nuisance calls is a priority for the Government. Our commitment to tackle this problem was outlined in our Nuisance Calls Action Plan, which was published on 30 March 2014. Since publication, we have progressed legislative and non-legislative measures, including ensuring improved information sharing between regulators and lowering the legal threshold for the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO). Currently we are encouraging and seeking more innovative and cost effective call blocking products and have launched a competition fund with Innovate UK to do this.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-22T16:06:42.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423062/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423062/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-19","Nuisance Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to tackle nuisance calls.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","901734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423063","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-22","<p>Policy responsibility for data protection policy, sponsorship of the Information Commissioner’s Office, and sponsorship of The National Archives transferred from the Ministry of Justice to the Department for Culture, Media and Sport, on 17 September. My department is working with the Information Commissioner and other stakeholders to effectively deliver the Government’s objectives in these areas. The National Archives remains a non-ministerial department.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-22T16:04:12.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423063/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423063/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-19","Information Commissioner and National Archives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his policy is on (a) data protection, (b) sponsorship of the Information Commissioner's Office and (c) sponsorship of the National Archives.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","901738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423064","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-22","<p>The Department for Business and the Cabinet Office have overall policy responsibility for the Digital Single Market. The Department for Culture Media and Sport leads on telecoms, audio visual policy, IT Security and now Data Protection. The Digital Single Market is a key priority for the UK Government and we welcome its ambition. It offers huge potential for jobs and growth and could increase UK GDP by up to 2%, and it can also benefit citizens, as shown by our recent deal within the European Council on roaming.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-22T16:03:22.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423064/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423064/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-19","Digital Technology: EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his policy is on the digital single market.","false","Biography information for David Warburton","Somerton and Frome","David Warburton","901740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423065","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-22","<p>I will be continuing the discussions with the Premier League about how best to support the game. Government believesthat given the size of the League's new TV deal, football's grassroots should receive greater investment than ever before, and we will work in partnership to ensure that this happens.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-10-22T16:22:37.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423065/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423065/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-19","Football: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to encourage the Premier League adequately to contribute to the financing of grassroots football.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Mr David Crausby","901739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423066","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-22","<p>A UK national commemorative event will take place on 1 July at the Commonwealth War Graves Commission Thiepval Memorial to the Missing of the Somme in France. This is a free ticketed event - the public ballot for tickets opened in September and will run until 18 November. There will be a daily service of remembrance at Thiepval on each of the 141 days of the Battle and a wide programme of events in the UK. Manchester will play a key role in this and I will announce further details shortly.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-10-22T16:21:12.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423066/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/423066/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-19","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans his Department has to commemorate the centenary of the Battle of the Somme.","false","Biography information for James Berry","Kingston and Surbiton","James Berry","901737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421899","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government does not collect data on the different types of unsecured debts and the creditors to whom they are owed across the full range of formal insolvency procedures.</p><br /><p>The Government acknowledges that some people are unhappy with the system of retentions as it stands, but it is an embedded feature of the construction industry.</p><br /><p>Therefore, our general approach is towork with the industry through the Construction Leadership Council and its supply chain payment charter; endorsing its commitment to zero retentions by 2025. Achieving this commitment will involve far-reaching changes to the way the sector works.</p><br /><p>It is not clear that requiring money to be placed in trust funds is the best way to overcome any shortcomings in the system of retentions: it would impose a financial burden on construction clients, many of whom are themselves small businesses, and where there is financial weakness, may itself make insolvency more likely. The Government is commissioning research on the costs and benefits of the retention system and alternatives, including the use of trust funds. This will inform future action.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","12255 ; 12256","2015-10-21T14:12:07.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421899/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421899/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-16","Construction: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the total amount lost by small firms in the construction sector because of bankruptcies among firms holding cash retentions in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","12233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421900","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government does not collect data on the different types of unsecured debts and the creditors to whom they are owed across the full range of formal insolvency procedures.</p><br /><p>The Government acknowledges that some people are unhappy with the system of retentions as it stands, but it is an embedded feature of the construction industry.</p><br /><p>Therefore, our general approach is towork with the industry through the Construction Leadership Council and its supply chain payment charter; endorsing its commitment to zero retentions by 2025. Achieving this commitment will involve far-reaching changes to the way the sector works.</p><br /><p>It is not clear that requiring money to be placed in trust funds is the best way to overcome any shortcomings in the system of retentions: it would impose a financial burden on construction clients, many of whom are themselves small businesses, and where there is financial weakness, may itself make insolvency more likely. The Government is commissioning research on the costs and benefits of the retention system and alternatives, including the use of trust funds. This will inform future action.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","12233 ; 12256","2015-10-21T14:12:07.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421900/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421900/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-16","Construction: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of cash retentions on the viability of small businesses in the construction sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warr