y information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL2667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421797","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>Stephen Shaw CBE, the former Prisons and Probation Ombudsman for England and Wales, has recently submitted his review into the welfare of vulnerable immigration detainees, including those with mental health difficulties and those who claim to have been victims of torture. He has recently submitted his report to Ministers at the Home Office and Department of Health. His findings are being carefully considered. The report will be published in due course by laying it before Parliament, alongside the Government’s response to the recommendations.</p><p>Doctors working in immigration removal centres have been reminded of the need to use the definition of torture set out in the case of R (EO &amp; Ors) v SSHD [2013] EWHC 1236 (Admin) when completing reports under Rule 35(3) of the Detention Centre Rules 2001.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2669","2015-11-02T12:16:08.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421797/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421797/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-15","Immigrants: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the recommendation by the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Refugees and the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Migration in the report of the inquiry into the Use of Immigration Detention in the United Kingdom published in March 2015 that the wording of the Government’s policy on the detention of individuals with mental illnesses should be changed to that which was in place before August 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL2668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421798","Home Office","false","2015-11-02","<p>Stephen Shaw CBE, the former Prisons and Probation Ombudsman for England and Wales, has recently submitted his review into the welfare of vulnerable immigration detainees, including those with mental health difficulties and those who claim to have been victims of torture. He has recently submitted his report to Ministers at the Home Office and Department of Health. His findings are being carefully considered. The report will be published in due course by laying it before Parliament, alongside the Government’s response to the recommendations.</p><p>Doctors working in immigration removal centres have been reminded of the need to use the definition of torture set out in the case of R (EO &amp; Ors) v SSHD [2013] EWHC 1236 (Admin) when completing reports under Rule 35(3) of the Detention Centre Rules 2001.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2668","2015-11-02T12:16:09.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421798/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421798/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-15","Immigrants: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the extent to which medical professionals are using the definition of torture as defined in <i>R (EO &amp; Ors) v SSHD</i> [2013] EWHC 1236 (Admin) when completing Rule 35 reports in respect of persons in immigration detention.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL2669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421799","Home Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>Asylum applications received from Syrian nationals who have not been brought to the UK as recognised refugees under the scheme will be processed in the normal manner. If they are found to have a genuine fear of persecution they will be granted asylum in the UK.</p><p>The UK will also deal with asylum applications from nationals of other countries in the normal way and the VPR scheme will not affect acceptance or support of those who are recognised as refugees here.</p><p>The VPR scheme, furthermore, does not impact on the Gateway or Mandate refugee schemes and the UK will continue to run these schemes together.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-10-29T17:08:26.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421799/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421799/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-15","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Scheme resettlement programme for Syrian refugees will affect the acceptance of and support for refugees from (1) Syria, and (2) other countries, whose applications are not within the programme.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL2670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421800","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-29","<p>The Freedom of Information Act applies to 100,000 public authorities and therefore its total cost is not recorded.</p><p>However, in evidence submitted by the Government to the House of Commons Justice Select Committee in 2012, it was estimated that the staff cost of replying to an FOI requesting central government was £184 and an internal review £179. Based on these calculations, and allowing for average pay awards, the estimated staff cost for central government requests and internal reviews was £9,600,000 in 2012, £10,100,000 in 2013, and £9,300,000 in 2014; and £4,600,000 for initial requests in January - June 2015. Information for the numbers of internal reviews handled in 2015 is not yet available.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-10-29T17:15:50.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421800/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421800/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-15","Freedom of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the total cost of administering the Freedom of Information regime in 2012–13, 2013–14 and 2014–15.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL2671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421801","Department of Health","false","2015-10-28","<p>The Department of Health received joint correspondence from Council of Deans of Health and Universities UK about a number of issues relating to healthcare education funding in England. A copy of the letter is attached.</p><br /><p>There have been no discussions with external stakeholders/bodies about the impact of potential changes to the funding of health care education and training in England, nor have any decisions been taken in this regard. The Department will consider all of its expenditure as part of the Spending Review (SR). The Government will announce the outcome of the SR on 25 November 2015.</p><br /><p>The Department has not made any formal assessment of the expected quality of placements of student nurses in the National Health Service in a free market in training places compared to a system of commissioned places funded by bursaries.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2673 ; HL2674","2015-10-28T12:26:51.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421801/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421801/answer","POC953467.pdf","POC953467.pdf","Healthcare Education Funding Letter","Healthcare Education Funding Letter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421801/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-15","NHS: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have received from the Council of Deans and Universities UK regarding the abolition of NHS bursaries; and whether they will publish any correspondence received.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2672"
